C directives are lines of code starting with a # character

Macros have a number of applications and you can see some of them as follows:
•Defining a constant
•Using as a function instead of writing a C function
•Loop unrolling
•Header guards
•Code generation
•Conditional compilation

the # and ## operators:
	the # operator used before the NAME parameter turns it into "copy" in the preprocessed code.
	The ## operator has a different meaning. It just concatenates the parameters to other elements in the macro definition


If a macro can be written as a C function, then you should write
a C function instead!

Conditional:
	$ gcc -o conditional conditional.c -D VAR
	$ ./conditional
	i+j = 110
	$ gcc -o conditional conditional.c
	$ ./conditional
	i+j = 210
	$

